{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_dogwood_ver01/data/sn84020358/00271744511/1907110101/0389.xml":{"full_text":"NEW HAVEN MORNING JOURNAL AND COURIER, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 1, 1907.\nAILING BEFORE\nECONOMIC CLUB\nVigorously Attacks the Policy\nof President Roosevelt\nToward Capital.\nFATAL FIXINGi\"0F RATES\nPower Taken from Railroads,\nTheir Properties Began\nto Decline and Credit\nDisappear.\n'Attorney John W. Ailing spoke last\nnight, at the annual banquet of the\nEconomic club, against the policy of\nPresident Roosevelt. His address was\non the general subject \"Is the Policy\nof President Roosevelt Toward Capital\ngound?\"\nMr. Ailing said, in part:\n\"My policy\"-r-not necessarily that\nof the Republican party but \"my\npolicy,\" for the carrying out of\nwhich I pledge my power as presi\ndent during my term, and shall see to\nIt that my successor shall be a pres\nident who will also carry It out, is that\nthe federal 'government shall have\nand exercise the power to control,\nregulate and restrain large business\nwealth engaged In interstate com\nmerce.\" Mr. Ailing after quoting Pres\nident Roosevelt continued:\nPresident Roosevelt Has succeeded\nJn creating the bureau of incorpora\ntions; In procuring power in the ln-\nCompare my advertising with\nthe rest of the advertising In\ntown?\nMine Is right up to date, Isn't\nIt? It shows I am Jlmmie on\nthe spot (and that spot is the\ncorner of CHURCH and CEN\nTER STREETS).\nNOW, TAKE IT FROM ME\nI am just as up to date on the\nseason's latest offerings as I am\non advertising.\nCOME IN AND SEE\nYOURS,\nDISBROW\nHE SELLS HATS.\nCor. 'Church and Center Streets.\nJEWELERS.\nOUR STOCK OF\nHALL\nCLOCKS\nis very complete and in\ncludes Hour and Half\nHour Striking Clocks, on\ngongs and, tubes; Tubular\nChiming Clocks, Fine\nBanjo Clocks.\ntMonson's\nJewelry Store.\n857-859 Chapel St.\nA Very\nLitte\nCompari\nson.\nof quality, variety\nof assortment and\nprices will serve\nto show that this\nis the place to buy\nLockets and Neck\nChains, whether\nsolid gold or gold\nniiea.\nJ. H. G. DURANT,\nJEWELER,\nOpposite Postofllce. 71 Church Street\nGIFT\nFOR A WEDDING\nSomething from our wares In either\nliver or cut glass is sure to suit your\nfancy and please the bride.\nr i\n78 Chapel St rest, NEW HAVEN, CT.\nMEET ME FACE TO FACE. I\ni 1 DID YOU EVER il\nli\nUerstate commerce commission to fix\nrates and otherwise regulate Inter\nstate railroads; and in procuring fed\neral statutes that railroad employes\nmay have limited hours of labor and\nmay recover for damages without re\ngard to their own negligence.\nHe now wants federal statutes by\nwhich all the traffic of railroads, with\nin as well as between States, shall be\nunder federal control, regulation and\nrestraint; by which all industrial cor\nporations doing an interstate busi\nness (and there are none which do\nnot), shall be obliged to take a fed\neral license or charter, and so be sub\nject to federal control, regulation and\nrestraint; by which a federal income\ntax, and a federal inheritance tax,\nshal be Imposed, not at all for the\nreason of raising revenue, (that is not\neven mentioned by him) but for the\npurpose of. reducing \"swollen for\ntunes\" advocating an Inheritance tax\non certain indefinite portions of in\ndefinitely large fortunes, of 100 per\nceo'.; in plain English, confiscation of\nsuch portions.\nHad it been abused? (the rate mak\ning power). Nobody claimed that it\nhad been. Mr. Roosevelt explicitly\nstated that railroad rates in\nthis country were reasonable. He\nsought for the power to fix rates on\nthe supposed groundvthat such power\ncould be used as a club to compel the\nrailroads to abandon rebating.\nThis whole matter of rebating, so\nfar as it effects the general public,\nhas been grossly exaggerated. Even\nnow President Mellen says: \"The pub\nlic cry has been against discrimina\ntion, yet those who have to handle\nthe business of railroads, know, ?that\nin private It is the one strenuous ef\nfort on the part of t,he public to se\ncure that very thing.\" Rebating was\na question between the wholesale\nshipper the intermediary and the\ncarrier. It did not affect the con\nsumer. The price to him was, would\nhave been, the same.\nNot only did President Roosevelt\nadmit that railroad rates were rea\nsonable, but every thinking man\nknew such to be the fact! and know\nthat the railroads had, of their own\naccord, and in the proper develop\nment of their business, been reducing\nrates all through their history, so that\nrailroad rates were lower In this\ncountry than in any other country.\nI Without State intervention, the rail\nroads voluntarily reduced their rates\nper ton per mile, from 3.048 cents in\n1863, to 0.763 cents in 1903; a re\nduction amounting, on the basis of\nthe business for 1903, and for that\nyear, to the enormous sum of $4,987,-\n040,622.\nIn 1903 the owners of the railroad\nstocks and bonds received a- return of\nonly 8.74 per cent, of the estimated\ntotal cost.\nThe rates of the railways are gov\nerned by economic laws, to which\ntheir managers must conform and\nwhich they cannot Ignore. For during\nall this period the natural tendency\nof the railway manager was to main\ntain such rates as the expanding traf\nfic would bear and clearly any appre\nciably lower rate would have wiped\nout altogether the small margin for\nthe profit of the owners.\nBut especially consider how Con\nnecticut, and all New England, de\npend for their salvation on the prac\ntice of this theory of rates. \"Vice\nPresident Byrnes told this club last\nwinter that the Consolidated railroad\nhauls the raw material for New Eng\nland manufacturers a thousand miles\nmoreor loss, at bare cost. Otherwise\nour manufacturers could not compete\nwith those nearer the base of raw ma\nterial. Not only does New England bring\nher raw material from afar, but It\nmust sell its manufactured product\nfar off. We must have here the low\nrate r the long distance haul, or we\nperish.\nNow the admitted fact is, that\nwhere railroad rates are fixed by the\nState, this correct theory of rates\nwill not be successfully applied. The\nState will not pay for the necessary\nability. There Is no.t the sharp spur\nof personal Interest. There is want\ning entirely the sense of protecting\nthe locality.\nSo state rates tend to rigidity. Grad\nually, Insensibly, the fact of distance\ncontrols. Under state, rate making\nNew England manufacturing will\nslowly but surely be wiped out.\nNow President Roosevelt is alone re\nsponsible for raising this railroad rate\nquestion. It was not a plank in the Re\npublican platform. In the senate it did\nnot command a majority of the Repub\nlicans in the senate committee. A mi\nnority of the Republicans and the\nDemocrats combined, and this Roose\nveltlan measure was entrusted to the\nDemocrat, Senator Tillman. The over\nwhelming popularity of President\nIRoosevelt jammed It through.\n.Now what has been the result? It is\npatent to everybody. From the Instant\nit appeared likely that the power to\nfix rates was to be taken from the\nrailroads and put into the hands of\ncommissioners In thex Interest of the\nshippers commissioners every one of\nwhom could be removed at once by\nMr. Roosevelt for what he might deem\n\"Inefficiency or neglect\" the value of\nrailroad properties began to decline\nand their credit to disappear.\nIn the meantime the business of the\ncountry was enormously increasing,\nand just at the time when the rail\nroads needed capital by the hundreds\nof millions to equip themselves for the\nwork to be done, their power to raise\nthe necessary capital vanished.\nFor who will come forward, except\nunder extraordinary Inducements, and\nput his money in an industry, the real\nmanagement and control of which is\nin the hands of an adverse or hostilo\ngovernment? The proposition is too ab\nsurd. The actual result Is that rail\nroads are obliged to stop Improve\nments. There is no money to pay for\nthem.\nThe havoc wrought by this Roose\nveltian crusade against railroad capi\ntal rune up into the billions of dol\nlars. It affects hundreds of thousands\nof individuals, every savings bank, ev\nery benefit society, every fire or life\ninsurance company, and through these\nsources, the whole community.\nAnd thiss so-called statesman. Pres\nident Roosevelt, not cojitent with the\nhavoc already wrought, is determined\nthat congress shall still further regu\nlate and control and restrain railroad\ncapital.\nIn carrying out his crusade against\nIndustrial capital, Mr. Roosevelt found\nil\n\nins, iiii i\nMEN'S BOOTS,\n$3, $3.50, $4, $4.50, $5, $5.50, $6, $7.\nMEN'S SLIPPERS, KID AND FELT,\n98c, $1.25, $1.50, $2, $2.25, $2.50, $2.75.\nBOYS', YOUTHS' AND LITTLE MEN'S,\n$1.25, $1.35, $1.50, $1.75, $2, $2.25, $2.50, $2.75, $3, $3.50.\nBoys', Youths' and Little Men's Slippers, Felt and Kid,\n75c, 85c, 1, $1.25, $1.50, $1.75.\nThe\nI\n,j..j.4.,j4.4f.,.4Nfr.H4\"M''l4\"W\nat hand the Anti-Trust Act .of 1890,\ncommonly, but erroneously, called the\nSherman Act. It prohibits all combin\nations in restraint of trade.\nYet it is mainly under this act that\nhis star prosecutions against the beef\npackers in Chicago, the Standard Oil,\nand the lAmerlean Tobacco Company\nhave been conducted.\nNow the beef packers in Chicago did\ncombine to get rebates; at least until\nthe Elklns Act of 1303, and probably\nlater. The administration procured a\ndecree under the Anti-Trust Act, that\nthe packers should cease combining in\nrestraint of trade. Then Mr. Garfield,\nthe chlof of the Bureau of Incorpora\ntions, was sent to investigate the beef\npacking Industry. His report was en\ntirely favorable. It conclusively show\ned that their vast business had been\ncarried on in a reasonable manner and\nfor moderate and reasonable profits.\nBut the investigation disclosed to Mr.\nGarfield (as is alleged) the rebate prac\ntices of the packers. His report on that\nsubject had never been made public\nby President Roosevelt, who alone\ncould authorize its publication.\nThereupon, all the United States Dis\ntrict attorneys In the United States\nwere directed to furnish to the De\npartment of Justice all the Informa\ntion they could find or get by grand\njury investigation or otherwise tend\ning to show that the packers had ob\ntained rebates since the Elklns Act.\nSuch prosecuting fury has never been\nknown In this country.\nThe administration, with great blow\ning of trumpets, commenced Its attack\non Standard Oil by an investigation\nhv the Bureau of Incorporations. As\na result, an indictment was returned,\nunder the Elklns Act, resulting in the\npenalty of twenty-nine millions of\ndollars, at which President Roosevelt\nexpressed himself as \"de-light-ed.\"\nBut this judgment will not stand.\nThere are many other valid objections\nto it, but It rests upon the proposi\ntion that a rate of freight, filed at the\noffice-of the Interstate Commerce Com\nmission at Washington, is established\nas if by act of congre&s, and that\nthough the shipper may inquire of the\ncarrier if it hm tecn tiled, and bo told\n86,\nWe mean by good shoes not only those that wear well, but those that fit well, look well and feel well. First and fore\nmost, the proper shape last must be had; then good leather and good workmanship will make good shoes (the kind we sell).\nThe ultra styles are the pointed toes, high heels and the short vamp effect, with the high-arched shank, and never has\na shoe been produced that will make a foot look so small and feel so comfortable as in shoes made on our short forepart, high\n'archecf shank last. Our seven-inch Boots, tan and black, ar made on this last. The High-Cut Boot, with spring and safety\nheel, for misses and children, in Vici Kid and Patent Colt, are very popular this Fall. The boys', youths' and little men's sizes\nin high cut are in stock. For men this Fall the lasts are not quite as pointed as last season, but narrow enough to make a well\nfitted foot look well. Patent Calf, Patent Colt, Gun Metal, Box Calf, Velour Calf, Wax Calf and Vici Kid ButtonLace and\nBlucher Cut, Double and Single Sole.\n.New\nIt had,' and though he pays the rate\nof freight stated by the carrier, with\nout asking or expecting or intending\nto get a rebate, yet, if the rate offered\ndiffers from the rate filed, though the\nshipper does not know It, yet the fed\neral statute lk violated, antf the ship\nper may be fined twenty-nine millions\nof dollars a monstrous gum, such as\none victorious belligerent state might\nImpose dn the defeated state, and that,\ntoo, In' face of the federal constitution\nwhich forbids excessive fines and pen\nalties. The Standard Oil company Is the fin\nest business organization In the world.\nIt employs 65,000 laborers. It has nev\ner had a labor strike. It does not owe\na dollar by way of bond or debenture,\nand has no floating debt. The volume\nof its business has always been, and\nis, enormous. The value of its proper\nty exceeds its 'capitalization several\ntimes over. It cannot be attacked for\nover-tapltallzatlon.\nIta general policy towards its com\npetitors has been to give them all a\nchance to come in with the big con\ncern on a fair basis. It is only a few\nwho have declined the suggestion, and\nas a rule they have not been success\nful, except in making a loud noise.\nOn the whole, the dominating pur\npose of the Standard has been to\nbroaden the consumption of its pro\nducts by decreasing cost, and so at\nlower prices. Yet it is this great in\ndustrial concern- which has brought\ndown upon it the wrath of President\nRooaevelt.\n(An action has been brought against\nit, and is now on trial, under the dis\ncredited Anti-Trust Act, to compel it3\ndissolution, for no other real reason\nexcept that It is big.\nI know so little about the pending\nsuit of the administration against the\nAmerican Tobacco company under the\ndiscredited Anti-Trust Act, to compel\nits dissolution, that I shall say but lit\ntle. Yet that company has outstanding\nsome forty millions of common stock,\nwhich has been worth over $200 per\nshare, or eighty millions some seventy-eight\nmillions of preferred stock,\nwhich has been worth about par and\nover one hundred millions of bonds\nI which are widely distributed.\nCIrsi's. 1\nIs\nillli: Mi Ml Sloes.\nONLY GOOD SHOES.\naven\n842 and 846 Chapel\nIt would eeem that an attack on a\nproperty like that should be based up\non serious and substantial reasons, af\nfecting the general public. I know of\nno alleged reason except the \"bigness\"\nof the company.\nPresident Roosevelt ha shown him\nself bitterly hostile to large corporate\nwealth. His aim has been to break it\nup. Ho has availed himself of federal\nstatutes, not so much to enforce them,\nas to destroy large business wealth.\nHe has disdained all party policy. In\nhis grand, lofty way it has always\nbeen \"my policy.\"\nThe constitution has not stood In his\nway. He has thrown aside the settled\nrule of its oonstruotlon since the Unit\ned States was created.\nMr. 'Roosevelt Is ignorant that finan\ncial credit, trust and confidence are\nthe pillars which support the glorious\ntemple of popular comfort, convenience,\nphilanthropy and well-being; and, like\nthe blind Samson, he would pull down\nthose pillars so as to secure the de\nstruction of his real or Imaginary Phil\nistines. It is true he Is Immensely popular\nwith the masses. So were the leaders of\nthe old Crusades against the unspeak\nable Turk. They did not do much\nharm to the Turk, but they brought\nuntold -misery on their blind followers.\nMr. Roosevelt is essentially like those\nold Crusade leadens. Powerful, arro\ngant, conceited, with a halo of heaven\nly inspiration, a born leader, bound\nby no pai;ty ties, himself the \"whole\nthing,\" In search of valiant deeds,\nclaiming a supernatural power to de\ntect and uncover and punish the\n\"wealthy malefastor,\" followed, as he\nthinks, by the whole people he is the\nmost dangerous force to constitutional\nliberty that has ever existed in this\ncountry.\nThe financial panic calls for an\nopinion as to how far \"my policies\"\nare responsible for It.\nLong continued would-wide prosper\nity naturally leads to over-lxpansion,\ndangerous speculation, strained credit,\nand high rates of interest, and conse\nquent depreciation in the security\nmarket But if the banking and\nmonetary system and general business\nconditions axe sound, other countries\nv i J\nBoys,\nWOMEN'S BOOTS,\n$2, $2.50, $3, $3.50, $4, $4.50, $5, $5.50, $6, $7, $8.\nMISSES' AND 'CHILDREN'S BOOTS.\n$1 $1 .25, $1 .50, $1 .75, $2, $2.25, $2.50, $3, $3.50.\nWOMEN'S SLIPPERS.\n$1 $1 .25, $1 .50, $1.75, $2, $2.50, $3, $3.50,\n$4, $5, $5.50, $6, $7. f\nMISSES' AND CHILDREN'S SLIPPERS, KID AND FELT,\n75c, 85c, $1, $1.25, $1.50, $1.75, $2, $2.50.\nShoe\nStreet.\nSi\ngenerally go through the tailing oft\nperiod of prosperity without explosive\npanics, and we do sometimes.\nBut we have a banking system un\nder the regulation, control and re\nstraint of the United States. Ever\nsince Andrew Jaokson'6 time it has\nbeen under condemna.tlon by banking\nand financial experts. There la not\ntime to point out why It continues to\nexist, except to say that the popular\nIdea is that the banks shall not have\nthe power to lssu ourrency which\nthey oug'ht to have, and which In pe\nriods of direst disaster they substan\ntially exercise without authority, in\nthe issue of Clearing House certifi\ncate currency; while on the other\nhand, banks are not unwilling to avail\nthemselves of such periods in order\nto get muoh hlffher rates (of Interest.\nBut the admitted and long continued\nincapacity of the United States to\nsuccessfully regulate the banking\nbusiness ought .to be a warning\nagainst extending that Incapacity to\nother fields of operation.\nNo other nation has such spasms of\n20, 50, 75, and 100 per cent, money as\nwe have had for two generations.\nSo I concede there is more danger\nhere, In the winding up of a period of\nprosperity, of a financial panic than\nelsewhere, and that It might and has\nheretofore occurred without the aid of\nour President\nThere have been only three large\npublio scandals; the Consolidated Gas\nof New York, the Life Insurance\ncompanies in New York, and the\nTraction systems In New York. In\nneither of these has President Roose\nvelt taken any part, nor could he.\nConsolidated Gas, after going\nthrough two severe Investigations, one\nlegislative and the other Judicial the\nlast one over a year In duration, has\ncome out triumphant In the report of\nthe master appointer by the court to\nascertain the facts.\nI have no doubt of the result of the\npending trial upon that report, ex\ncept that as I notice a new Roose\nveltlan Judge is to decide the case.\nBut neither nor all of these scand\nals could have caused the existing\ngeneral Impairment of credit.\nIt ia now. about three years ago. In\ni\n\ntj\n\nt\nt\n\nt\nX\nt\n\nr\na. jtt.nrnr, nriannli of TalA. t-\nr n.iciSu, xn, (j., mat\npeople py the proposition that thai\nUnited States government\n\"regulate, control, and restrain\" thei\nlarge business wealth engaged In in-!\nterstate business. in\nvigorous, combative, fighting way, he1\nnaa strenuously prodded the publio, j\non the stumo and bv\nprodded congress, and that, too,\nseverely prodded the Judiciary, and It,\nis the panlo alone whloh Is said to I\ngive us a rest\nHe has been conncloim thn.t ia wa\nmaking a prodigious stir, ana warned;\ntnai it would bring on a panlo. He;\nhas noticed tiow general market\nvaluesthe true Index of credit\nwould rise on the hope that he would1\nlisten to the suggestions made to hlmi\nand would BlumD off on hearinat the1\nsame old warlike trumpet blasts.\nm mx judgment. It has been \"my,\npolicies\" which have been the prlnci-,\npal and direct oause la bringing on'\nthe panto. If not so, why has there\nnot been a panlo In Germany, France\nand England, where 'there la the!\nsame tailing oft of a long period of\nprosperity? There J3 no panlo, norj\nlikely to be any, In any other coun-i\ntry than the United States, i i\nHADDAM MAN MISSING,\nPurchased Goods at Clothing Store\nThen Disappeared.\nMiddletown, Oct 31. The polica;\nhere were notified to-day of the disap-J\npearance of B. C. Broome of(Middhv\nHaddam, who came to thi city last:\nTuesday and has not been sesn by h!!\nfriends or relatives since. Mr. Brooms,\ncame from Jersey City recently with)\nhis wife and took up his residence at)\nMiddle Haddam. j\nHis wife says she knows of no ren-i\nson for his disappearance. Th po-j\nlice have learned that he want to a\nclothing store here to make some pbr-i\nchases, which was the last seen of!\nhim. He Is descttoea as iturty-nve\nyears of age, lx fed in height. Men\nder, weight 150 pjuuds, smjota face,\nlight -brown liair aud blm cfta.","height":"28544","width":"19644"}}
